<h2>About</h2>
A natural carbohydrate made of corn sugar treated and fermented with the bacteriaÂ <em>Xanthomonas campestris.Â </em>

In the gluten-free cooking, It plays the crucial role of imitating gluten. In baking, gluten is what makes dough sticky, elastic and viscous.

Because baked goods made with regularÂ flours depend on gluten for structure, those made with gluten-free flours will often require a thickener to keep them from crumbling. MostÂ gluten-free baking recipes suggestÂ Xanthan Gum. For aÂ cup of gluten-free flour use 1 tsp of xanthanÂ for cakes and cookies and 2 tsp of for breads and pizza.
